WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.880
And I just want to caveat everything. This talk will be focused on R, but know that the

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:11.760
strategies we're going to be talking about are abstract and could apply to any programming

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:18.559
language, Python, etc. So what I'd like for you all to do is picture the scene. You've

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:23.840
just launched your first machine learning model into production as a Plumber API, and

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:32.000
your team loves it. Word gets out over a few weeks, and suddenly other teams want to start

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.520
consuming your API as well. Maybe they use it as part of a feature in their Shiny application.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:45.680
Maybe they use the predictions as a feature in another downstream predictive model. The

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.959
point is that your new service, this wonderful service called Appy, has now created value

00:00:51.959 --> 00:00:58.279
across various segments of your organization, and you've done the equivalent of a data science

00:00:58.279 --> 00:01:08.120
grand slam, and all is good. That is, until it isn't. You show up to work one day, and

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:13.080
the Slack messages start pouring in. It's like, hey man, I was trying to prototype a

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:18.519
new feature in Shiny, and I'm not getting any responses back from your API. What's with

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:24.800
that? Or another team may message you and say, hey, we're getting cascading failures

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:31.160
in our ETL pipeline because we can't get your predictions for our machine learning

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:38.440
model or something like that. So we're starting to struggle at this point. And you and your

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:43.919
manager, you go through the logs and you see that your app is still up, it's still running.

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:50.480
The issue is that it's struggling to handle all of this new traffic that it's receiving.

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:57.440
So this brings us to an important question, which is, how can we make our plumber APIs

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:07.160
more performant? Some of you may be in this talk, and you have never made a REST API before.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:13.080
Not even sure what REST is. And that's awesome. We're happy to have you here. A quick recap

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:20.360
of what REST is, it's just a URL, but instead of returning a web page, it returns some junk

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:26.520
that looks like this. Which is called JSON. And I want you to just take my word for it

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:37.880
that this powers a lot of the modern web today. API performance is a huge topic that spans

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:43.800
all sorts of ideas. And we won't be able to cover all of them in today's talk. So instead,

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:50.000
we're going to focus on two ideas, two strategies. We're going to talk about minimizing serialization

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.559
costs and maximizing responsiveness with async programming. And we're going to cover these

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:02.960
in particular because they will improve your REST API performance. They're relatively they

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:07.960
require relatively minimal code changes, and there's great R packages for implementing

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:14.160
them. So let's move to the first strategy. Minimizing

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:23.360
serialization costs. So when I say that, what does that mean? So the idea here is that serialization

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:30.119
costs are the time it takes for you to take an R object in memory and turn it into some

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:38.399
format that you can send over the wire. Like JSON. Right? You can optimize the business

00:03:38.399 --> 00:03:43.119
logic of your API endpoints, but at the end of the day, there's going to be this serialization

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:51.559
cost that you pay to turn your R object that's going to be the API response into JSON.

00:03:51.559 --> 00:03:58.960
So there's an opportunity here to focus on to start to zero in on, like, how your objects

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:03.800
are being serialized to see if there's an opportunity to improve performance.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:10.639
So to think about, like, why this matters, I want you all to consider a scenario. I have

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:17.119
a party, and I'm going to invite 100 people to this party. 200 doesn't matter. And I have

00:04:17.119 --> 00:04:22.440
two options. I can either send the invites through a handwritten postcard or I can send

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:28.920
them through e-mail. To send all of these invites through postcard, I have to go get

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:33.959
the postcards. I have to sit there and handwrite 100 postcards. Then I have to put them in

00:04:33.959 --> 00:04:39.920
the mailbox and then wait for them to get to their intended recipient. Versus with e-mail,

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:45.440
I can write my message essentially once and then send it to everybody on a distribution

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:51.880
list and because of the Internet, it's essentially instantaneous.

00:04:51.880 --> 00:05:00.480
We want our serialization cost to be closer to e-mail than to postcards. Because if we

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:05.239
do that, we're going to be able to return our responses much faster. If we can return

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:09.959
results faster, we're going to be able to handle more requests, things of that sort.

00:05:09.959 --> 00:05:16.920
So sounds like a decent deal, good idea. How can we do that? So I have here a simple

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:26.279
example of a Plumber API that uses a, that uses what's called a serializer function to

00:05:26.279 --> 00:05:31.480
swap out the defaults and then get a performance boost. So how we go about doing this, the

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:39.160
first step is find a package that serializes JSON faster. Out of the box, Plumber uses

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:45.799
something called JSON Lite, which is a robust battle-tested package. It's great. But in

00:05:45.799 --> 00:05:54.160
this example here, I'm using something called YYJSONR, which uses a very fast C library

00:05:54.160 --> 00:06:02.760
under the hood to read and write JSON in record times.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:06.399
So once you've found your package of choice, then what you're going to do is you're going

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:14.720
to write this little function, YYJSONRSerializer, and what that's going to be used is it's going

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:20.559
to be used as a special function that you give to Plumber so it knows how to turn your

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:26.640
R objects into whatever you're serializing it to.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:33.239
So with that serializer function, from there, it's very simple. You can go ahead and just

00:06:33.239 --> 00:06:38.359
use this serializer tag to say that you want to use your new serializer, and then your

00:06:38.359 --> 00:06:43.700
endpoint gets an immediate performance boost. There's no need to change the underlying business

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:49.119
logic of your API endpoint. You just get the lift for essentially free.

00:06:49.119 --> 00:06:55.160
Now, on this tiny app, you're thinking, like, this isn't a huge deal. But if you can imagine

00:06:55.160 --> 00:07:00.160
an API with 100 endpoints, then it starts to become, like, great from a maintenance

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:05.000
standpoint as well, because now I can just change the serializer on my 100 endpoints,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:13.320
and I get improvement across all of them. So we go back to our little web service, Appy,

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:17.720
and we go ahead and we change out his serializer, and he gets a nice speed boost. He gets a

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:22.619
sick set of roller skates. So now whereas he was trudging along before, now he's gliding

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:27.160
through a little quicker. But we're not done yet. We can improve Appy

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:32.799
even more by using the second strategy that we have here, which is maximizing responsiveness

00:07:32.799 --> 00:07:37.959
with async programming. Now, to understand this strategy, we need

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:45.519
to take a quick sidebar to understand how R and Plumber works out of the box. So when

00:07:45.519 --> 00:07:52.279
you have our API here on the left and our incoming requests on the right, how does Plumber

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:58.959
process these? R, I mean, Plumber is an R package, and R is single-threaded, meaning

00:07:58.959 --> 00:08:06.920
that it can process one instruction at a time. So when those three API requests come in,

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:12.880
your Plumber API is going to munch through each one of them sequentially.

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:20.119
Now for a lot of REST services, this, like, synchronous execution model is perfectly fine.

00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:24.119
Especially if you have your API has, like, low to moderate traffic and the end points

00:08:24.119 --> 00:08:29.920
are relatively snappy. There's plenty of synchronous web services out there today.

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:36.119
But when your traffic becomes higher, and your end points can vary in terms of their

00:08:36.119 --> 00:08:42.719
execution time, then this model of execution can start to get hairy pretty quickly. And

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:48.719
to understand why, I want you to imagine that with these three requests, one is slower than

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:57.280
two and three. Say one takes ten seconds, and two and three take two seconds apiece.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:03.000
The first request is going to take ten seconds, but now request two doesn't just take two

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:08.919
seconds, it takes 12, because it has to wait for request one to complete. And what's worse,

00:09:08.919 --> 00:09:13.359
request three will have to wait a grand total of 14 seconds, because it has to wait for

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:19.359
the other two requests to finish. And you can imagine beyond three requests, you know,

00:09:19.359 --> 00:09:23.599
if you're getting hit with a thousand requests, then you're going to start to dog pile your

00:09:23.599 --> 00:09:28.659
R process, and it's not going to be a good time.

00:09:28.659 --> 00:09:34.479
So we need another execution model. And that's where async programming comes in. I like to

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:39.000
think of async programming as just waiting or executing computations without waiting

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:47.280
for them to complete. But, like, intelligently. It's computational multitasking.

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:51.200
To make it a little more concrete, I want you to imagine, like, two ways of going about

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:58.640
your day. One is that you go, you brew a pot of coffee, you pour yourself a cup, drink

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:03.239
it, then you get your bread, put it in the toaster, and then when it's done, you enjoy

00:10:03.239 --> 00:10:08.799
your toast. Versus the way I think the way that a lot of us do it, naturally, is you're

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:12.159
going to wake up, you're going to start a pot of coffee, you're going to throw your

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:16.119
bread in the toaster, and then you're going to wait for each of those things to complete,

00:10:16.119 --> 00:10:19.479
and, you know, maybe you'll sip on your coffee while the toast is finishing, but you're ultimately

00:10:19.479 --> 00:10:25.020
going to be able to do those two tasks simultaneously without waiting for them to finish.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:29.719
And so what we want is an execution model that's closer to way two. And that's where

00:10:29.719 --> 00:10:34.780
async programming gets us, or what async programming gets us.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:40.580
So how does this work for something like Appy? So what's going to happen is, instead of having

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:45.539
just one R process that's running our API, what we're going to do instead is we're going

00:10:45.539 --> 00:10:52.299
to spin up a certain number of child processes. And what we do then is our main R process

00:10:52.299 --> 00:10:57.380
is going to function essentially as, like, a relay, where as the requests come in, our

00:10:57.380 --> 00:11:04.880
API will direct them to one of these workers where the requests will actually get processed.

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:12.419
And so in doing this, we end up with this nice effect where request one takes ten seconds,

00:11:12.419 --> 00:11:18.059
but now requests two and three now both take two seconds to complete, because they're sent

00:11:18.059 --> 00:11:24.200
to dedicated workers and there's no longer a line, essentially.

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:31.559
So that sounds like a good deal. That sounds good. So how do we go about implementing this

00:11:31.559 --> 00:11:44.000
in code? So to do that, you may have heard of something called Mirai by now. It's a great

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.400
package for doing asynchronous programming, and it's the one we're going to use in this

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:55.880
example. But you may be wondering, well, why not use the future package? The future

00:11:55.880 --> 00:12:01.359
package has been around for a while. It's another durable battle-tested package that

00:12:01.359 --> 00:12:07.359
works in a variety of contexts, and it was used in the first ‑‑ it has been used

00:12:07.359 --> 00:12:15.320
for asynchronous plumber work and whatnot up until today. I'm choosing to use Mirai

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:20.919
in this example for reasons that are kind of like beyond the scope of this talk, but

00:12:20.919 --> 00:12:30.359
I'm happy to talk to folks about it later. So how can we go about doing this? So we have

00:12:30.359 --> 00:12:36.719
this basic example. It's another hello world example. And the way that we're going to go

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:42.960
about doing this is we're going to use a function called Mirai from Mirai called daemons, which

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.599
is going to spin up four workers in this example, four R processes that are going to be lurking

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:55.559
in the background there waiting to do stuff. And then what we're going to do next is our

00:12:55.559 --> 00:13:02.000
business logic, okay, and our API endpoint is then going to basically get bundled up

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:08.679
and passed into another Mirai function called Mirai. And what that Mirai function is going

00:13:08.679 --> 00:13:14.599
to do is it's going to take the R expression or, like, the business logic that you've

00:13:14.599 --> 00:13:21.280
passed it, and it is going to run that code in the child R process.

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:26.320
And then the important thing is that when it's running or after it runs, it's going

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:30.559
to immediately return something. It's going to return something called a promise. And

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:36.599
the way to think about a promise is that it is a placeholder for the eventual result of

00:13:36.599 --> 00:13:46.119
a computation. Now, this notion of a promise, I'll kind of hand wave here, but the idea

00:13:46.119 --> 00:13:56.280
of a promise is what allows our API process to remain responsive to other incoming requests.

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:01.159
Because when the promise returns or, like, when we get our promise back, the main R thread

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:06.359
is free to do other things, like intercept another inbound request. And the nice thing

00:14:06.359 --> 00:14:12.359
about Mirai is that once this promise is ready to go, when there's a result able to

00:14:12.359 --> 00:14:18.280
be fetched, it's going to inform the main R process directly, and then R is just going

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:25.440
to send that result back to the client that requested it.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:33.919
So we go back to Appy, and we instrument some of his code with some async programming inside

00:14:33.919 --> 00:14:38.440
of it, and he gets another speed boost. He gets this sick jet pack. So now he's not just

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:42.559
rolling along the street. He's rolling with, like, a Mach 8 engine or something like that,

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:49.760
something real fast. And the end of Appy's story is that with these two strategies, it

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:56.119
was sufficient for the web service to scale to meet the demands that our other teams were

00:14:56.119 --> 00:15:01.799
bringing to it, and all is right with the world again.

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:10.799
Now, with that, what have we learned from Appy's story? So just kind of recap. We have

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:15.719
these two strategies that we talked about, which is minimizing serialization costs, you

00:15:15.719 --> 00:15:21.080
know, really try to drive down the time it takes to turn our R objects into something

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:29.919
that can be sent over the wire, and two, to keep our main application responsive by

00:15:29.919 --> 00:15:37.119
using asynchronous endpoints or async programming in general.

00:15:37.119 --> 00:15:42.039
And then there's kind of like this third point that I think underlies, like, the two of these

00:15:42.039 --> 00:15:47.799
things, which is, you know, R is much more powerful than you think it is. We have a lot

00:15:47.799 --> 00:15:53.559
of sophisticated tooling today that allow us to make very powerful, shiny apps, or in

00:15:53.559 --> 00:15:58.719
this case, plumber APIs. So a lot of the times, like, folks on Hacker News may tell you that,

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:03.400
like, R is great for prototyping but not production. They'll tell you to take your API and write

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:10.039
it in, like, Rust or something like that. Myself and other people at this conference

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:18.119
are here to tell you that you don't have to do that. A lot of API design or solid performance

00:16:18.119 --> 00:16:24.299
is about solid design, not programming languages. So I encourage you all to take some of these

00:16:24.299 --> 00:16:29.200
strategies that I've shown you today and use them in your own projects and see how they

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:38.320
can take your own web services to new heights. So that's me. If any of you would like to

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:43.239
talk about any of this further or just kind of hang here at the conference, I'm happy

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:47.440
to talk to you all. And then there's a QR code here to take you to some of the other

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:58.840
ways that you can get a hold of me. But that's what I got. I'll take any questions you have.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:06.479
Thank you so much. So we do have time for one question here. So what was the learning

00:17:06.479 --> 00:17:12.199
curve to Mirai for someone who hasn't used async programming before? And is future simpler

00:17:12.199 --> 00:17:19.400
for a newbie to learn the concept of async? I do think that there is a learning curve

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:27.479
with async. You do have to kind of wrestle with it for a little bit. I think that you

00:17:27.479 --> 00:17:36.160
can go either way between Mirai and future. Both of them have just great APIs for, like,

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:41.319
working with them. They're very user-friendly. So you can't go wrong with either one.

00:17:41.319 --> 00:17:47.839
Okay. And is there a lot of overhead cost in using Mirai, startup, et cetera?

00:17:47.839 --> 00:17:53.359
Yeah. So that's a great question. Because the overhead, right, can come from the idea

00:17:53.359 --> 00:17:58.920
where now that we have these other processes, you have to send the data, right, your requests

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:03.079
over to these processes. And there's some overhead with funneling data between processes

00:18:03.079 --> 00:18:11.719
on the server. In my experience, like, running some local testing before the conference here,

00:18:11.719 --> 00:18:15.560
I actually noticed that with the more recent versions of Mirai, like, the overhead cost

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:21.319
is, like, next to nothing, which is really cool. So I wouldn't worry too much about it.

00:18:21.319 --> 00:18:26.800
Amazing. We have one more question here. So does Mirai run on a single thread? If so,

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:30.959
does this affect the user experience and UI responsiveness?

00:18:30.959 --> 00:18:37.119
So the important thing is that so with R, everything is always single-threaded. The

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:42.520
idea is that instead of doing multi-threading, we're doing what's called multi-process, which

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:48.119
is where so, like, if you spin up this API with several workers and you open, you know,

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:52.880
like, activity monitor or Windows task scheduler or, like, whatever the monitor is, you'll

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:57.680
see that along with, like, your API process, there will be, like, other R sessions that

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:06.640
are running in the background. So it really shouldn't impact the user experience in the

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:10.800
way that I think, like, multi-threaded code could, but...

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:16.439
Great. And I think we have one more question here. Why are faster serializers not the default

00:19:16.439 --> 00:19:22.000
for Plumber? I feel like I might as well just kick that

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:27.040
over to Thomas at this point. Yeah, he's better got ass than me. The only thing that I'll

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:35.280
say is that, you know, choosing default dependencies for packages is a really complex thing, right?

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:41.640
Because certain packages may be really fast, but they may only have, like, one maintainer

00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:47.359
that doesn't really work with the project anymore. So you got to choose your dependencies

00:19:47.359 --> 00:19:52.000
wisely there. Great. Thank you so much.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:52.560
Yeah, thank you.

